<li><p>
Extracting the Data by Request
</p><p>
In the previous example, we used the default GET method to send form input
to the server. We also assumed the register_globals directive in the php.ini
file was turned "On," allowing PHP to create local variables with the form data.
</p><p>
In the following example, we assume that register_globals is turned "Off"
(the recommended and default setting) and that the method is POST,
the more commonly used method when working with form input.
</p><p>
This method sends the form input as a message body in the HTTP header to the
server and does not append the data to the URL in the browser.
Even though the input data is sent using a different method,
it is received in the same URL-encoded format.
</p><p>
When register_globals is turned off, we must use built-in PHP special variables,
called "super-global arrays", to access the form information.
</p><p>
Because we do not cover arrays until later in the course, we will use the PHP
<b>extract()</b> function and the super-global array <b>$_REQUEST</b> to
create local variables to hold input data from the form.
</p><p>
The <b>$_REQUEST</b> array contains all of the input data for both GET and POST
methods. Once <b>extract($_REQUEST)</b> is executed the HTML
form's parameters will be assigned to PHP variables of the same names.
</p>
